  <discussion type="conservation">of conservation concern;</discussion>
  <discussion>Subspecies tephrodes differs from subsp. niveus, which is not known to occur north of Mexico, by having less densely hairy phyllaries and generally broader leaves (larger leaves more than 3 cm broad). Both differ from H. petiolaris subsp. canescens (H. niveus subsp. canescens) by lacking the conspicuous white-villous tufts (“beard”) of the median cusp of the paleae in the center of the head that characterize H. petiolaris.</discussion>
  <discussion>Subspecies tephrodes is in the Center for Plant Conservation’s National Collection of Endangered Plants.</discussion>
